{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534063"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:42:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:42:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14889"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14889"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.1,0.05,0.46,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7580"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59196"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7580"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14889"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44607"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1784"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4384"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18528"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35970"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43569"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59196"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for her first antenatal visit at eight weeks gestation. She has no significant medical history and takes only folate supplements. Her booking bloods reveal her rubella antibody level is 8 IU/mL (\u0026gt;10). She is concerned about the risk of infection during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The remainder of her antenatal screening tests are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No vaccination required as natural immunity will develop","Immediate MMR vaccination","MMR vaccination at 20 weeks gestation","MMR vaccination immediately after delivery","MMR vaccination at six weeks postpartum"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario presents a common clinical situation where routine antenatal screening reveals that a pregnant woman is not immune to rubella (antibody level \u0026lt;10 IU/mL). The management of this finding requires careful consideration of both maternal and fetal risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMMR vaccination immediately after delivery\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management plan. Live vaccines, including MMR, are contraindicated during pregnancy due to the theoretical risk of congenital rubella syndrome. However, it is important to protect both mother and future pregnancies by ensuring immunity is achieved. The immediate postpartum period, before discharge from hospital, is the optimal time to administer the vaccine to ensure compliance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate MMR vaccination\u003C/strong\u003E during pregnancy is contraindicated due to the theoretical risk of vaccine strain virus causing congenital infection. Although there is no evidence of harm when MMR has been inadvertently given in pregnancy, intentional administration should be avoided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMMR vaccination at 20 weeks gestation\u003C/strong\u003E is also contraindicated for the same reasons as immediate vaccination. The risk of congenital rubella syndrome remains throughout pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMMR vaccination at six weeks postpartum\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessarily delayed and risks missing the opportunity to vaccinate. There is no benefit in waiting this long, and earlier vaccination provides protection sooner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo vaccination required\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as natural immunity will not develop without exposure to the virus, which could be dangerous during pregnancy. Active immunisation is necessary to protect against future exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring pregnancy, the woman should be advised to avoid contact with anyone with suspected rubella infection. It is also important to document her non-immune status clearly in her medical records to ensure postpartum vaccination is not missed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["MMR vaccine is contraindicated during pregnancy due to theoretical risks of congenital rubella syndrome.","Non-immune pregnant women should receive MMR vaccination in the immediate postpartum period.","Rubella immunity should be checked as part of routine antenatal screening.","A rubella antibody level less than 10 IU/mL indicates non-immunity."],"references":["Australasian Society for Infectious Diseases (ASID). Management of perinatal infections. East Melbourne: ASID; 2022 [cited 2024 Nov 5]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ASID-Management-of-Perinatal-Infections.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44607"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14889"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44607"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-05T15:31:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-05T15:32:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7580"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59196"}}},"m